				\begin{document}$$B = \left( {B_{i,j} } \right)$$\end{document} (this is the higher level application of the Hungarian algorithm, see Fig. 2) results with the optimal permutation of the peptides. Given the permutation of the peptides, and using the permutation calculated in the lower level, we obtain the full permutation of the molecule’s atoms. This permutation has the desired property of maintaining the peptides structure as well as the protein sequence, and is the optimal one among all such permutations.Fig. 2
